Task 2: Design and Implement a Health-Aware Multi-Service Stack
Problem Statement
Design and implement a Docker Compose application consisting of exactly four services 芒聙聰 a PostgreSQL database, a Redis cache, a Node.js HTTP API, and an Nginx reverse proxy 芒聙聰 such that each service starts only after every service it depends on has passed a container-native health check. The API must expose a /health endpoint that reports the live connection status of both the database and the cache. The Nginx proxy must not start until the API health check passes. All service credentials and ports must be supplied exclusively through a .env file; no credentials may be hard-coded in docker-compose.yml or application source files.

Acceptance Criteria
Running docker compose up -d from a clean state (no running containers, no named volumes) brings all four services to healthy status within 120 seconds, as shown by docker compose ps reporting healthy for every service that defines a health check; the Nginx proxy must be the last service to reach running state.

A GET request to http://localhost/health through the Nginx proxy returns HTTP 200 with a JSON body that contains a services object listing both database and cache as "connected", confirming that the API successfully reached both backing services after startup.

Task 3: Implement Failure Injection and Automated Recovery Validation
Problem Statement
Design and implement a shell script named validate-resilience.sh that programmatically tests three failure scenarios against the running stack: (a) stopping the PostgreSQL container and confirming the API /health endpoint returns HTTP 503 within 15 seconds, then restarting PostgreSQL and confirming the API returns HTTP 200 again within 60 seconds; (b) stopping the Redis container and confirming the API continues to serve data from the database (HTTP 200 on /api/users) even without the cache layer, then restarting Redis and confirming the health endpoint reports cache as "connected" within 60 seconds; (c) stopping the webapp container and confirming Nginx returns HTTP 502 or 503 within 10 seconds, then restarting the webapp and confirming Nginx proxies successfully within 60 seconds. The script must print a clearly labelled PASS or FAIL result for each of the three scenarios and exit with code 0 only if all three pass.

Acceptance Criteria
Running bash validate-resilience.sh against the live stack completes all three scenarios and prints PASS for each one, then exits with code 0; no scenario may rely on sleep values longer than 5 seconds between individual readiness polls, and the entire script must finish within 4 minutes.

After the script completes, docker compose ps shows all four services in running state with health checks reporting healthy, confirming that the automated restart policy (restart: unless-stopped) restored every service without manual intervention.

Expected Outcomes
You will have a fully operational four-service Docker Compose stack in which startup order is enforced by health checks and dependency conditions, not by arbitrary sleep timers.
You will have a repeatable shell script that proves the stack recovers automatically from individual service failures, giving you a concrete model for dependency management in production-style container environments.
Conclusion
This lab required you to move beyond simple depends_on ordering and implement genuine readiness gating through health checks, environment-driven configuration, and automated failure validation. The patterns you applied here 芒聙聰 health-conditioned dependencies, graceful degradation, and restart policies 芒聙聰 are the same patterns used in production container orchestration. Extend this foundation by exploring how Kubernetes liveness and readiness probes map directly to the health check concepts you configured in Docker Compose.
